 literature: prose narrative, verse narrative, and, primarily, lyric poetry. In the final chapter, Braden turns to the poetry of Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz to demonstrate a sophisticated case of Petrarchism taken to one of its extremes within the walls of a convent in seventeenth-century Mexico.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEuropean poetryyRenaissance, 1450-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aLove poetry, EuropeanxHistory and criticism. 0aLove poetry, Romance-languagexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aGreenberg, Martin08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package Archivez978311053801440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300147285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300147285.jpg  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles